Arkansas River - Random Forest Testing on GDE Plant Functional Groups

Matthew Lurtz

2025-10-20

Science Question

The main goal in this manuscript is to test if a given plant functional group (e.g., response variable, NDVI derived from Planet Imagery) has a stronger correlation or dependence with a specific hydroclimatic variable (e.g., covariate, groundwater depth or rainfall, or temperature, etc.). Notably, we will also test if this dependence changes with respect to the temporal resolution (i.e., daily, weekly, and monthly) at which we regress the covariates on the response variable and how the depedence changes during wet and dry years.

Methodology

The approach is multifaceted:

  1. Straight forward application of Random Forest to deduce the most predictive covariates in NDVI and see if they differ based on plant functional group (PFG) using a daily temporal resolution. All the major PFGs will be compared to the NDVI response of fallow land. This approach will be carried out using the entire population of data and then repeated after separating the response variable and covariates into wet and dry years.
  2. Straight forward application of Random Forest to deduce the most predictive covariates in NDVI and see if they differ based on plant functional group (PFG) using weekly and monthly temporal resolutions. This will make for a direct comparison to approach no. 1.
  3. In order to detrend and-or deseasonalize the response variable, Singular Spectrum Analysis is applied to the response variable to decompose the time series from the annual periodicity.

Wet and Dry Years, Defined

  1. Use differences in discharge.

  2. Use differences in rainfall.

  3. Use differences in reservoir release.

  4. Use differences, from prior years, of snowpack in upper Arkansas watershed.
